<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-292-990  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 292 990.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  April 2 1990 pA7A(W) pB7F(E) 11 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Two groups blast Bell companies' gloomy assessment. (ConsumerFederation of America, International CommunicationsAssociation)(Bell companies assert that the US is becoming asecond-rate telecommunications power)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Carnevale, Mary Lu.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Economics and Technology Inc has prepared a study for the ConsumerFederation of America and The International CommunicationsAssociation that refutes the assertion, propagated by the Bellcompanies, that the US is becoming a second-ratetelecommunications power.andP;  The study says the Bells' claim 'islittle more than a transparent fiction,' noting that the US is farahead of Japanese and European competitors.andP;  The study indicatesthat Bell companies have engaged in a disinformation campaign,trying to influence Congress to lift restrictions that prohibitBell companies from participating in long-distance and informationservices, and from manufacturing communications equipment.andP;  TheBell companies reply that the Consumer Federation and theInternational Communications Association are misguided.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Economics and Technology Inc. (research).andO;Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesTelephone companiesDeregulationGovernment RegulationConsumer Federation of AmericaInternational Communications AssociationInformation servicesCommunications EquipmentForeign CompetitionUnited States. Congress.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>